Ho Chi Minh is elected president of North Vietnam On March 2nd, 1946, and signs an agreement with France recognizing Vietnam as an autonomous state in the Indochinese Federation and French Union as part of a larger series of negotiations following the French overthrow of the DRV government in the south and advance northward. This created a temporary peace between the DRV and the French that lasted until November of 1946, when tensions exploded following the Haiphong Incident. Open hostilities broke out in Hanoi. Ho Chi Minh along with his government went underground, fleeing to the forested mountains and hills to the west. 



